<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1724,1989]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">
Elytron with humerus strongly projecting posterolaterally, lateral carinae clearly delimitated from humerus to apex. Apex subrounded, with a minute spicule in marginal side. Punctures minute and dense at anterior half, becoming shallower and sparse at distal third. Yellowish sparse pubescence more dense in distal third. Legs with femora and tibiae sublinear; metafemora extending to third urosternite. Apex of urotergite and urosternite transversely truncate. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,320,1862,1885]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific epithet is a Latin adjective, feminine gender, meaning imitator, and refers to the appearance of an insect of the 
<taxonomicName box="[348,509,1897,1920]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Chrysomelidae</taxonomicName>
subfamily 
<taxonomicName box="[630,762,1897,1920]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Galerucinae">Galerucinae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
